    th1_title:      "1. What is Cryptographic Hashing?",
    th1_body:       "A hash function takes any input and produces a fixed-size output (digest). SHA-256 always produces 256 bits = 32 bytes = 64 hex characters, regardless of input size. Even a one-character difference creates a completely different hash — this is called the avalanche effect.",
    th1_p1_title:   "One-Way",
    th1_p1_desc:    "Cannot reverse the hash to get the original input",
    th1_p2_title:   "Fixed Length",
    th1_p2_desc:    "Always 64 hex chars regardless of input size",
    th1_p3_title:   "Avalanche Effect",
    th1_p3_desc:    "1 bit change → ~50% different hash bits",
    th1_p4_title:   "Deterministic",
    th1_p4_desc:    "Same input always produces the same hash",
    th1_p5_title:   "Collision Resistant",
    th1_p5_desc:    "Practically impossible to find two inputs with the same hash",
    th1_p6_title:   "Fast Computation",
    th1_p6_desc:    "Efficient enough for real-time use",

    th2_title:      "2. What is HMAC?",
    th2_body:       "HMAC (Hash-based Message Authentication Code) adds a secret key to hashing. This proves both integrity (message wasn't changed) and authenticity (sender knows the key). HMAC is defined in RFC 2104 and is widely used in APIs, TLS, and session tokens.",
    th2_b1:         "Without HMAC, an attacker can modify a message and compute a new valid hash — they don't need the key because SHA-256 alone is keyless.",
    th2_b2:         "With HMAC, computing the correct signature requires the secret key. Even if an attacker sees both the message and the HMAC, they cannot forge a new valid HMAC without the key.",

    th3_title:      "3. The HMAC Formula — click any term!",
    tt_kopad:       "opad = 0x5C (01011100) repeated 64 times.\nXOR with key to form outer padding — creates a different inner layer.",
    tt_kipad:       "ipad = 0x36 (00110110) repeated 64 times.\nXOR with key to form inner padding — binds the message to the key.",
    tt_m:           "m = the message you want to authenticate.\nCan be any length.",
    th3_leg1:       " — SHA-256 hash function",
    th3_leg2:       " — Key padded/truncated to 64 bytes",
    th3_leg3:       " — 0x36 × 64 (inner pad)",
    th3_leg4:       " — 0x5C × 64 (outer pad)",

    th4_title:      "4. Why Two Nested Hashes?",
    th4_body:       "The double hashing prevents length-extension attacks. If HMAC were simply H(key ∥ message), an attacker who knows the hash could extend the message and compute a valid hash without knowing the key. The inner hash binds the message to the key, and the outer hash wraps the result with a different key-derived value. An attacker who only sees the final HMAC cannot forge a valid HMAC for an extended message.",

    th5_title:      "5. Key Normalization — Why 64 Bytes?",
    th5_body:       "SHA-256 processes data in 512-bit (64-byte) blocks. The key must match this block size: if shorter, it is padded with zeros to reach 64 bytes. If longer, it is first hashed with SHA-256 (producing 32 bytes) and then padded to 64 bytes. This ensures consistent block alignment regardless of the key length you choose.",

    th6_title:      "6. Real-World Usage of HMAC",
